## if-else Statement

The `if-else` statement is used when there are two possible outcomes in a program. It executes one block of code if 
the condition is true and another block if the condition is false. This statement helps programs handle both situations
effectively and improves decision-making capabilities. The `if-else` statement is widely used in applications where
different actions are required based on user input or specific conditions. Examples include checking whether a number
is even or odd, determining pass or fail status, and user authentication systems. It makes programs flexible and easier
to understand because all possible outcomes are clearly defined. The `else` part acts as an alternative path when the 
main condition is not satisfied.

**Example:**

```javascript
if(age >= 18)
console.log("Adult");
else
console.log("Minor");
```

### Advantages of if-else Statement

* Handles two possible conditions easily
* Improves program decision-making
* Makes code more organized
* Helps in controlling execution flow
* Easy to understand and implement

### Disadvantages of if-else Statement

* Becomes difficult with many conditions
* Large nested structures reduce readability
* Can make code lengthy
* Complex logic becomes harder to manage
